        "This memorial invites us to contemplate Mary's spiritual martyrdom—though she did not shed her blood, she suffered in her heart as she witnessed her Son's agony. Her sorrow was not passive acceptance but active compassion (meaning 'suffering with'). She freely chose to stand at the foot of the Cross when the apostles fled, uniting her will with her Son's sacrifice.",
        "The feast also reminds us that Mary understands human suffering. Because she experienced profound sorrow, she can console those who suffer. The traditional prayer to Our Lady of Sorrows asks: 'Most holy and afflicted Virgin! Queen of Martyrs! You who stood beneath the Cross, witnessing the agony of your dying Son, look with a mother's tenderness and pity on me, who kneel before you.' Mary's sorrows make her not distant but deeply compassionate toward all who suffer.",
